{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":4545,"record_hash":"sha256:16881ec7ca49ada0aea06728f0c4452dfc52a5c60febf8eb0f85c108b10a5edf","timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:49:10.269Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"{\"status\":{\"[REDACTED:entropy]\":{\"completed\":\"**Findings**\\n\\n::code-comment{title=\\\"[P2] JSON keys bypass redaction\\\" body=\\\"Object member names are copied with key.clone(), so a source_record that places a token in a map key is stored verbatim while source_record_redacted can remain false. For a POC-small fix, either redact suspicious keys with collision-safe placeholders or make the value-only scope explicit wherever this redactor is surfaced.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\\\" start=40 end=46 priority=2 confidence=0.86}\\n\\n::code-comment{title=\\\"[P2] Sensitive field names do not affect values\\\" body=\\\"The object walk redacts values without passing key/path context, and should_redact only uses entropy/hex shape. Common structured secrets such as authorization headers, AWS access key IDs, or human passwords under keys like token, api_key, secret, password, or authorization can survive and be reported as unredacted. A tiny sensitive-key denylist for string values would fit the POC better than a dependency.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\\\" start=99 end=102 priority=2 confidence=0.8}\\n\\n::code-comment{title=\\\"[P3] Git hashes look like secrets\\\" body=\\\"is_random_hex redacts any 32+ byte high-entropy hex string, which includes normal Git object IDs and commit SHAs in transcript/tool output. That can erase important provenance from captured sessions. If this tradeoff is intentional, document it; otherwise consider a small contextual exemption for clearly Git-labelled hashes rather than broad framework-style secret scanning.\\\" file=\\\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\\\" start=115 end=119 priority=3 confidence=0.9}\\n\\nI did not see the surrounding POC docs overstating this as publish-safe redaction; the notes correctly say transcript capture is opt-in/local-only and publication needs a stronger policy. The main risks are the guard’s blind spots and the SHA-style over-redaction above.\"}},\"timed_out\":false}","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:49:10.269Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}